<subSubSection id="7FDF8CBDFF80FF96FF20103B236EFC41" pageId="8" pageNumber="53" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="377ADF36FF80FF96FF20103B236EFC41" blockId="8.[136,789,658,951]" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FF20103B236EFC41" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Haec species a congeneris indumento stellato-fasciculato, foliolis coriaceis marginibus valde revolutis apice rotundatis atque inflorescentia raro ramosa distinguitur.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7FDF8CBDFF80FF96FF20108423FAF86B" pageId="8" pageNumber="53" type="description">
<paragraph id="377ADF36FF80FF96FF20108423FAF86B" blockId="8.[136,788,991,1949]" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FF20108421BCFC01" box="[174,225,992,1015]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Tree</emphasis>
c. 13 m tall; young stems with dense golden stellate-fasciculate indument, glabrescent. 
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FD0B109B2387FBE1" box="[645,730,1023,1047]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Petioles</emphasis>
2.8- 5.4 cm, with sparse strongly appressed golden stellate indument. 
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FE881724200CFBA1" box="[262,337,1088,1111]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Leaves</emphasis>
with 3-8 subopposite to alternate leaflets; rachis 2.7-10 cm, keeled above, glaucous with sparse, strongly appressed golden stellate indument; petiolule 1-5 mm or leaflets sometimes subsessile, with sparse golden stellate-fasciculate indument, glabrescent; leaflet blade 3.2-10 × 1.5-3.5 cm, oblanceolate to occasionally elliptic, very coriaceous, flat in pressed material, glabrous and glossy above, glabrous and dull below, base asymmetrical, acute to cuneate, margins strongly revolute with up to 3 mm rolled under in dried material, apex rounded, midvein slightly raised above, distinctly raised below, slightly glaucous, with sparse appressed golden stellate indument, secondary veins 12-16 per side, flat to slightly impressed above, raised below, tertiary venation slightly raised and evident above. 
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FDA7156723E5F9ED" box="[553,696,1539,1563]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Inflorescence</emphasis>
axis 6- 19 cm, unbranched, or bifurcating towards the apex, reddish, essentially glabrous with very sparse golden stellate-fasciculate indument; bracts c. 0.3 mm, triangular; pedicels 2.5-3.5 mm, 0.3-0.4 mm in diam., densely golden strigulose and also with appressed golden stellate-fasciculate trichomes. 
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FEBA15A020E3F92A" box="[308,446,1732,1756]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Male flowers</emphasis>
with a cupulate, 5- or 6-lobed calyx, the lobes c. 0.5 × 0.5 mm, triangular, acute, glabrous outside, densely golden setaceous inside; stamens 8, filaments c. 4.5 mm, glabrous except for sparse trichomes toward the base, anthers c. 1.1 × 0.4 mm, ellipsoid; disc and pistillode densely golden setaceous, the trichomes to 0.5 mm. 
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FF6214E120D6F86B" box="[236,395,1925,1949]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Female flowers</emphasis>
not seen. 
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FE7114E22364F86B" box="[511,569,1926,1949]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Fruit</emphasis>
not seen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7FDF8CBDFF80FF96FCD0127F24E6FDA0" pageId="8" pageNumber="53" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="377ADF36FF80FF96FCD0127F24E6FDA0" blockId="8.[824,1475,282,598]" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FCD0127F2573FEC4" box="[862,1070,283,306]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Conservation status</emphasis>
. – Although 
<taxonomicName id="F0C5A4B5FF80FF96FB4D127F24F4FEC4" box="[1219,1449,282,306]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="8" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="betamponensis">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FB4D127F24F4FEC4" box="[1219,1449,282,306]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Beguea betamponensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the fairly well-protected Betampona Strict Nature Reserve (
<figureCitation id="AFFEC3B3FF80FF96FC69123F2578FE85" box="[999,1061,347,371]" captionStart="Fig. 4" captionStartId="6.[136,163,1315,1334]" captionTargetBox="[136,786,276,1300]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[136,786,276,1300]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 4. – Geographic distribution of Begueo opetolo Capuron (circles), B. birkinshowii G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (stars), B. boreolis G. E. Schatz &amp; Lowry (diamond), B. tsorotononensis G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (squares) and B. turkii G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (triangles), mapped on the bioclimatic zones of Madagascar (after CORNET, 1974; see SCHATZ, 2000)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/888183/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), its current status with regard to population size and reproduction, and also the potential negative impact from invasive strawberry guava (
<taxonomicName id="F0C5A4B5FF80FF96FB6412F822DCFE23" authority="Sabine" authorityName="Sabine" authorityYear="1821" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Psidium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="8" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cattleyanum">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FB6412F8249EFE42" box="[1258,1475,412,436]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Psidium cattleyanum</emphasis>
Sabine
</taxonomicName>
), is unknown. With a restricted AOO and the potential threat from such an aggressive invasive, which could rapidly push the species to “Critically Endangered” or “Extinct” status, 
<taxonomicName id="F0C5A4B5FF80FF96FCB6117B22BEFDC0" box="[824,995,542,566]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="8" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="betamponensis">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FCB6117B22BEFDC0" box="[824,995,542,566]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">B. betamponensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is here assigned the category of “Vulnerable” [VU D2] using the IUCN Red List Criteria (
<bibRefCitation id="5354A2C7FF80FF96FAAF115A24F2FDA0" author="IUCN" box="[1313,1455,574,598]" firstAuthor="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="IUCN Species Survival Commission, Gland &amp; Cambridge" pageId="8" pageNumber="53" refId="ref13043" refString="IUCN (2012). IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. 2 nd ed. IUCN Species Survival Commission, Gland &amp; Cambridge." title="IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. 2 nd ed." type="book" year="2012">IUCN, 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7FDF8CBDFF80FF96FCD011E422CDFC0A" pageId="8" pageNumber="53" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="377ADF36FF80FF96FCD011E422CDFC0A" blockId="8.[824,1475,639,1020]" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FCD011E422C8FD61" box="[862,917,640,663]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Notes</emphasis>
. – 
<taxonomicName id="F0C5A4B5FF80FF96FC3A11E425CDFD61" box="[948,1168,639,663]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="8" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="betamponensis">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FC3A11E425CDFD61" box="[948,1168,639,663]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Beguea betamponensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the type collection in humid forest at the Betampona Strict Nature Reserve (
<figureCitation id="AFFEC3B3FF80FF96FC1211A42281FD2E" box="[924,988,704,728]" captionStart="Fig. 7" captionStartId="10.[136,163,1905,1924]" captionTargetBox="[136,1454,276,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[136,1454,276,1869]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 7. – Begueo birkinshowii G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry. A. Flowering branch; B. Detail of flower at anthesis; C. Portion of inflorescence axis. [Birkinshow 159, MO] [Drawing: R. L. Andriamiarisoa]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/888189/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
), where it is sympatric with 
<taxonomicName id="F0C5A4B5FF80FF96FA9E11A5242AFD2E" box="[1296,1399,704,728]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="8" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="apetala">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FA9E11A5242AFD2E" box="[1296,1399,704,728]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">B. apetala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It can be easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="F0C5A4B5FF80FF96FBEB118525BEFD0E" box="[1125,1251,736,760]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="8" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="galotensis">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF80FF96FBEB118525BEFD0E" box="[1125,1251,736,760]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">B. galokensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with which it shares an indument of tufts of very short golden stellate-fasciculate trichomes, by its very coriaceous leaflets with strongly revolute margins, rounded apex lacking a mucro, and impressed secondary veins (vs subcoriaceous leaflets with slightly revolute margins, acute to acuminate apex with a distinct mucro, and flat to slightly raised secondary veins) and its occasionally branched inflorescences (vs unbranched inflorescences) (
<figureCitation id="AFFEC3B3FF80FF96FCCE108022DFFC0A" box="[832,898,996,1020]" captionStart="Fig. 6" captionStartId="9.[113,140,1905,1924]" captionTargetBox="[141,1421,276,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[141,1421,276,1869]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 6. – Begueo betomponensis G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry. A. Flowering branch; B. Portion of inflorescence axis; C. Detail of flower at anthesis. [Andrionorisoto et ol. 246, MO] [Drawing: R. L. Andriamiarisoa]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/888187/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="53">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
